Preheat your #oven{} to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7.

Chop the @potatoes{450%g} into 2cm wide wedges (no need to peel).

Pop the wedges onto a large #baking tray{}. Drizzle with @oil{}, season with @salt{} and @pepper{}, then toss to coat. Spread out in a single layer.

> Use two baking trays if necessary.

When the oven is hot, roast on the top shelf until golden, ~{25-35%minutes}. Turn halfway through.

Remove the @slow cooked beef{280%g} from the packaging. Place in an #ovenproof dish{} along with the juices and cover loosely with #foil{}.

Roast on the middle shelf for ~{25-30%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: Ensure the beef is piping hot throughout.

Trim and halve the @cucumber{1}. Thinly slice half the cucumber into rounds - this will go in the baos.

Halve the remaining cucumber lengthways. Chop into roughly 1cm wide strips, then chop into 1cm pieces.

Zest and halve the @lime{1/2}.

In a #medium bowl{}, add the @coleslaw mix{120%g}, chopped cucumber, three quarters of the @mayonnaise{64%g} and a good squeeze of lime juice.

Season with salt and pepper, then toss to combine. Set your slaw aside.

Once cooked, remove the beef from the oven, reserve 1 tbsp cooking juices per person, then discard the foil and any remaining cooking juices.

Use two #forks{} to shred the beef as finely as you can. Stir through the @hoisin sauce{64%g}, lime zest and reserved beef juices.

Place the @bao buns{4} (2 per person) on a #plate{} and microwave, 750W: ~{1%minute 30 seconds} / 900W: ~{1%minute}.

> If you don't have a microwave, place the bao buns onto a baking tray. Bake on the middle shelf until warm and fluffy, ~{2-3%minutes}.

When everything's ready, transfer the bao buns to your plates. Spread the remaining mayo inside the buns and top with the hoisin beef and cucumber slices.

Serve with your wedges and creamy slaw alongside. Enjoy!